"""
Christ Layer fill — Revelation chapters 1-5 (missing verses only)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-revelation-1-5-fill.py

Fills all missing verses not written by the original zc-christ-revelation-1-5.py:
- Ch 1: vv 1-16, 18-20 (v17 already present)
- Ch 2: all 29 verses
- Ch 3: all 22 verses
- Ch 4: all 11 verses (throne room; thematic connection to Christ)
- Ch 5: vv 1-5, 7-11, 13-14 (vv 6, 12 already present)

merge_comm never overwrites existing entries -- safe to re-run.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

REVELATION_CHRIST = {
  "1": {
    "1": """<p>A direct revelation: 'The revelation of Jesus Christ, which God gave him to show to his servants the things that must soon take place.' Christ is simultaneously the subject and the mediator of the entire book -- God gives the revelation <em>to him</em>, and he sends it through his angel to John. The Christological claim is structural: the unveiling of history's end belongs to the Son because the Father has given him authority over all history (John 17:2; Dan 7:14). Every vision that follows is Christ's own disclosure of what is coming.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>A direct revelation: John bore witness to 'the word of God and to the testimony of Jesus Christ, even to all that he saw.' The phrase <em>martyria Iesou Christou</em> (testimony of Jesus Christ) frames the entire book as Christ's own witness -- he is both the witness and the content witnessed to (1:5: 'the faithful witness'). John's role is faithful transmission of what Christ shows him, grounding the book's authority in Christ's self-disclosure rather than an independent human vision.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>A direct revelation: the first of Revelation's seven beatitudes -- 'Blessed is the one who reads aloud the words of this prophecy, and blessed are those who hear, and who keep what is written in it.' Christ's words create blessing: to receive and keep his prophetic word is itself a gift of grace. 'The time is near' (<em>ho kairos engys</em>) anchors the whole book in eschatological urgency rooted in Christ's imminent return -- every chapter is read in the shadow of his coming.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>A thematic connection: grace and peace flow from a triune source -- 'him who is and who was and who is to come' (the Father; cf. Exod 3:14), 'the seven spirits' (the Spirit in sevenfold fullness, Isa 11:2), and verse 5 adds 'Jesus Christ.' Christ stands as the third member of the triune source of all covenant blessing. The Trinitarian greeting in a Jewish epistolary opening establishes that grace and peace -- Israel's covenant blessings -- now come through the Father, Spirit, and the crucified-risen Son together.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>A direct revelation: three Christological titles -- 'the faithful witness' (his earthly ministry of truth-telling, culminating in the cross); 'the firstborn of the dead' (Col 1:18 -- the resurrection establishes his primacy over all who will follow him from death); 'the ruler of kings on earth' (Ps 2:2 -- the one judged by Pilate now reigns over all rulers). The ground for all three: 'to him who loves us and has freed us from our sins by his blood.' The titles flow from the atonement.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ 'has made us a kingdom, priests to his God and Father.' Exodus 19:6 -- Israel's failed vocation as a 'kingdom of priests' -- is now constituted by redemption rather than commandment. The church is a priestly kingdom not because it has kept the law but because Christ freed it by his blood (v5). 'To him be glory and dominion forever and ever' -- the church's priestly vocation issues directly in worship of Christ, making the redeemed community the vehicle of perpetual doxology.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>A direct prophecy: 'Behold, he is coming with the clouds, and every eye will see him, even those who pierced him.' Two OT texts applied directly to Christ: Daniel 7:13 (the Son of Man coming with clouds to receive the kingdom) and Zechariah 12:10 (mourning for the one they have pierced, fulfilled in John 19:37). The one executed outside Jerusalem as a criminal will return in public, unmistakable, cosmic glory. 'Even so, Amen' -- the double affirmation seals the certainty of his return.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I am the Alpha and the Omega, says the Lord God, who is and who was and who is to come, the Almighty.' Though spoken by the Father here, Revelation 22:13 assigns the same title to Christ. John deliberately uses the same divine self-description for both -- the same technique as the Gospel of John (John 1:1: 'the Word was God'). The Alpha and Omega encompasses all of history from creation to consummation; that title belongs to Christ because he is the one in whom all things cohere (Col 1:17).</p>""",
    "9": """<p>A thematic connection: John is a 'partner in the tribulation and the kingdom and the patient endurance that are in Jesus.' Every aspect of John's Patmos exile -- suffering, kingdom-belonging, perseverance -- is experienced <em>in Jesus</em>. The solidarity of the exalted Christ with his suffering servants (Heb 4:15; 2 Cor 1:5: 'as we share abundantly in Christ's sufferings') means that the servant's suffering participates in the pattern of the master's own suffering, which was the path to the kingdom.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>A direct revelation: John is 'in the Spirit on the Lord's Day' when he hears the voice behind him. 'The Lord's Day' (<em>kyriake hemera</em>) is the day of Christ's resurrection, already distinguished from the Sabbath in early Christian practice (Acts 20:7; 1 Cor 16:2). To be in the Spirit on the resurrection day is to receive the Spirit Christ poured out from his risen glory (John 20:22; Acts 2:33). The entire vision is given through the Spirit of Christ on the day that commemorates his victory over death.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ commands John, 'Write what you see in a book and send it to the seven churches.' The risen Christ commissions the prophetic writing -- the authority of the Apocalypse is not John's visionary experience but Christ's command to record and transmit. The seven churches are chosen by Christ as the first recipients of his word. Every subsequent reader of Revelation receives a letter that Christ addressed through John to the whole church.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>A thematic connection: John turns to see the voice and sees 'seven golden lampstands.' The lampstands are the seven churches (1:20), and Christ walks among them (2:1). The temple's menorah (Exod 25:31-40) represented Israel's priestly vocation of bearing light; here the churches are the lampstands, and Christ is present among them as the source of their light (John 8:12). The church's light is derivative -- it shines only because Christ walks in its midst and holds its messengers in his right hand.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>A direct revelation: 'one like a son of man' (Dan 7:13) clothed in a long robe and golden sash -- the risen Christ in glory. Daniel 7:13 describes the son of man approaching the Ancient of Days to receive the kingdom; here Christ already wears the robe of priestly-royal authority (the long robe, <em>podere</em>, is the high priest's garment in the LXX of Exod 28:4). Jesus is simultaneously the enthroned king, the high priest interceding for his churches, and the fulfillment of the Danielic vision of the glorified Son of Man.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>A direct revelation: 'the hairs of his head were white, like white wool, like snow.' This applies Daniel 7:9 -- the description of the Ancient of Days himself -- to Christ. The eternal attributes of the Father are the attributes of the glorified Son: the same divine whiteness that marked the uncreated God now marks the incarnate, crucified, risen Lord. 'His eyes were like a flame of fire' -- all-penetrating moral sight that sees past appearance to the reality of each church (2:2, 9, 13, 19; 3:1, 8, 15).</p>""",
    "15": """<p>A direct revelation: 'his feet were like burnished bronze, refined in a furnace, and his voice was like the roar of many waters.' The feet like refined bronze suggest absolute moral purity in standing. The voice like many waters is drawn from Ezekiel 43:2 -- 'the glory of the God of Israel was coming... and the sound of his coming was like the sound of many waters.' The glory of YHWH returning to his temple in Ezekiel is now the glory of the risen Christ present among his churches on earth.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>A direct revelation: 'in his right hand he held seven stars, from his mouth came a sharp two-edged sword, and his face was like the sun shining in full strength.' Three images: (1) seven stars -- the messengers of the churches whom Christ holds and directs (1:20); (2) the sword from his mouth -- Isa 49:2 (the servant's mouth as a sharp sword); Heb 4:12 (the word of God as living and piercing); his word is his weapon of conquest and judgment; (3) face like the sun -- the Transfiguration's temporary glory (Matt 17:2) is now Christ's permanent resurrection state.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I am the living one. I died, and behold I am alive forevermore, and I have the keys of Death and Hades.' The resurrection is not merely a past event but Christ's permanent status: 'I live' (<em>zon eimi</em>, present tense). The keys of Death and Hades belong to him because he passed through both doors and came out on the other side (1 Cor 15:55-57). The vision John falls at his feet to receive begins with this three-part credential: divine identity, resurrection reality, eschatological authority over death.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ organizes the entire prophetic book in his commission to John: 'Write therefore the things that you have seen, those that are and those that are to take place after this.' The three-part structure -- past vision (vv12-18), present condition (chs 2-3), and future events (chs 4-22) -- is Christ's own architecture. He does not merely appear in the book; he structures it. The book of Revelation is organized by the risen Christ's command, making it his prophetic testament to his churches.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ explains the mystery -- 'the seven stars are the angels of the seven churches, and the seven lampstands are the seven churches.' The angels (messengers or guardians) of the churches are held in his right hand -- under his authority. The lampstands are the churches among whom he walks. The governing image of Christ's relationship to the church throughout the book is this: he is present, active, and sovereign among the gathered communities -- he holds them and walks within them.</p>"""
  },
  "2": {
    "1": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ identifies himself to Ephesus as 'him who holds the seven stars in his right hand, who walks among the seven golden lampstands.' The self-identification is pastoral: to Ephesus, whose love has cooled, he presents himself as the one who is actively present and walking among them. His presence is not passive; he walks, observes, and knows the full condition of each congregation. The one they must rekindle love for is the one who is already walking in their midst.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I know your works, your toil and your patient endurance.' The omniscient Christ knows what no human evaluator can know: the full record of works, toil, and perseverance. He also knows their doctrinal discernment -- 'you cannot bear with those who are evil' -- and their testing of false apostles. The pastoral vision of Christ is comprehensive and particular: he knows each church's full history of faithfulness and failure. This is the same all-seeing gaze identified in 2:23 as the divine prerogative.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>A direct revelation: 'You have borne up for my name's sake, and you have not grown weary.' Christ specifically honors endurance that is <em>for his name</em> -- not abstract perseverance but faithfulness directed toward him. The name of Jesus is the content of their witness and the reason for their suffering (Acts 5:41; 3 John 7). What the world sees as weakness Christ commends as costly fidelity. His acknowledgment of their endurance is itself a form of reward -- the one they endured for recognizes and names what they bore.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>A direct revelation: 'But I have this against you, that you have abandoned the love you had at first.' Christ speaks as the covenant partner who can name the departure. The first love is the love they owed him before their orthodoxy became routine. Correct doctrine without love for Christ is the Ephesian danger -- and Christ names it as abandonment, not merely coolness. The church that tests false apostles and hates the Nicolaitans has nonetheless left the one whom all their testing and hating should have served.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Remember from where you have fallen; repent, and do the works you did at first. If not, I will come to you and remove your lampstand from its place.' Christ holds the power to remove the lampstand -- to withdraw his presence from a congregation. A church without Christ's presence is no longer a church in the Revelation sense. The three steps -- remember, repent, do -- are the path back. Christ is not sentimental about congregations that have abandoned him, however orthodox their confessions remain.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Yet this you have: you hate the works of the Nicolaitans, which I also hate.' Christ's moral character is the standard for the church's discernment. What he hates defines what his people should reject. The Nicolaitan teaching (likely sexual immorality and compromise with the imperial cult) is not merely wrong in the abstract -- Christ specifically hates it. The church's faithfulness in this particular is commended because it reflects Christ's own moral seriousness about the boundary between the church and the world's idolatries.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>A direct revelation: 'To the one who conquers I will grant to eat of the tree of life, which is in the paradise of God.' Christ restores what Adam forfeited (Gen 3:24 -- the flaming sword guarding the tree of life). Access to the tree of life is the eschatological promise of Revelation 22:2,14 -- and Christ personally grants it to the conqueror. He speaks as the one who has authority over paradise itself (Luke 23:43: 'today you will be with me in paradise'). The first letter's promise is Eden restored -- a new creation gift from the new Adam.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ identifies himself to Smyrna as 'the first and the last, who died and came to life.' To a church facing martyrdom, Christ presents his own death and resurrection as the credential for speaking. He has already gone where he asks them to go -- through death to life. The self-identification 'who died and came to life' is not merely informational; it is pastoral: the one who speaks knows from the inside what he is asking, and he asks it as the pioneer who has already passed through death and returned victorious.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I know your tribulation and your poverty (but you are rich).' The sovereign inversion that marks Christ's kingdom throughout the NT (Matt 5:3; 2 Cor 6:10; James 2:5): the materially poor church is spiritually rich because Christ is their possession. The 'synagogue of Satan' -- those who claim covenant identity but reject Christ -- illustrates that true covenant membership in the new age is defined by relationship to Jesus, not by ethnic or institutional claim (Rom 2:28-29; Gal 3:29).</p>""",
    "10": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Be faithful unto death, and I will give you the crown of life.' The martyr's promise from the one who himself was faithful unto death (Phil 2:8). The crown of life (<em>stephanos tes zoes</em>) is the victor's wreath given to those who endure trial (James 1:12). Christ gives the crown as the one who first received it -- he who endured the cross, despising its shame, received the joy set before him (Heb 12:2). The promise is not cheap: it is given by the one who went through death first.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>A direct revelation: 'The one who conquers will not be hurt by the second death.' The second death (Rev 20:14 -- the lake of fire) is overcome because Christ has already conquered death. The promise flows from 1:18 -- Christ holds the keys of Death and Hades. Those united to him by faith participate in his conquest: because he died the death sin deserved and rose victorious, those in him will not face the second death. The martyr in Smyrna who faces the first death is precisely the one who will not face the second.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ presents himself to Pergamum as 'him who has the sharp two-edged sword.' The sword proceeding from his mouth (1:16) is the word of God (Heb 4:12; Isa 49:2). To a church in a city dominated by Roman imperial power and the cult of the divine emperor, Christ presents the counter-claim: his word is the ultimate sword -- not the Roman <em>gladius</em> the proconsul wielded, but the word that creates, judges, and will finally conquer all human power (19:15,21). The true authority in Pergamum is the one speaking through John.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I know where you dwell, where Satan's throne is. Yet you hold fast my name, and you did not deny my faith, even in the days of Antipas my faithful witness, who was killed among you.' Christ honors Antipas with the title 'my faithful witness' (<em>ho martys mou ho pistos</em>) -- the exact title that belongs to Christ himself in 1:5. To die bearing Christ's name is to share Christ's own martyr-identity. The language of martyrdom in Revelation is Christ-shaped: the faithful witness who is killed is a type of the original faithful witness.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>A direct revelation: 'But I have a few things against you: you have some there who hold the teaching of Balaam, who taught Balak to put a stumbling block before the sons of Israel, so that they might eat food sacrificed to idols and practice sexual immorality.' Christ names the sin by its OT precedent -- Numbers 25:1-2; 31:16. Balaam's strategy was compromise with idolatry through sexual temptation; the Pergamum teachers offer the same accommodation to Rome's imperial cult. Christ identifies the pattern across centuries, showing himself as the one who holds all of Israel's history in view.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>A direct revelation: 'So also you have some who hold the teaching of the Nicolaitans.' The Nicolaitan teaching -- which Christ hates (2:6) -- has a presence within the congregation at Pergamum alongside the Balaam-teachers. Christ sees the doctrinal ecology of each congregation with perfect clarity. The juxtaposition of external pressure (Satan's throne, Antipas's martyrdom) and internal compromise (Balaam, Nicolaitans) captures the dual front on which the church always fights: the world's violence and the church's own accommodation.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Therefore repent. If not, I will come to you soon and war against them with the sword of my mouth.' Christ threatens direct, personal disciplinary intervention against false teaching within the congregation. His coming (<em>erchomai</em>) here is a realized judgment within history, not only the final parousia. The sword of his mouth (his word) is the weapon: the same word that creates the church is the word that judges corruption within it. Invitation and threat come from the same mouth.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I will give the hidden manna' and 'a white stone, with a new name written on the stone that no one knows except the one who receives it.' Hidden manna: the manna placed in the ark (Exod 16:32-34; Heb 9:4) is the type; Christ as the true bread from heaven (John 6:35,48-51) is the antitype -- the nourishment no idol-food can provide. The white stone with a new name is an intimate, personal promise: Christ knows and gives each believer a name only he and that person share, marking the depth of individual union with the risen Lord.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ presents himself to Thyatira as 'the Son of God, who has eyes like a flame of fire, and whose feet are like burnished bronze.' 'The Son of God' -- Psalm 2:7 ('You are my Son') stands behind this royal title. The attributes (burning eyes, burnished feet) recall 1:14-15 and the Danielic figure, now explicitly connected to divine sonship. To a church tolerating Jezebel's sexual immorality, Christ presents himself as the penetrating moral judge whose gaze passes through every pretense to the reality beneath.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I know your works, your love and faith and service and patient endurance, and that your latter works exceed the first.' Christ commends genuine growth -- the Thyatiran church is doing more than it once did. The fourfold commendation -- love, faith, service, patient endurance -- maps the full shape of Christian life. Christ watches and measures growth in faithfulness, and he names it. His recognition of their progress is not passive; the one who knows the last works exceed the first was present through every stage of their growth.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>A direct revelation: 'But I have this against you, that you tolerate that woman Jezebel, who calls herself a prophetess and is teaching and seducing my servants to practice sexual immorality and to eat food sacrificed to idols.' The OT Jezebel (1 Kings 16:31; 19; 21) introduced Baal worship into Israel through Ahab. The Thyatiran prophetess re-enacts the same strategy: using prophetic authority to normalize idolatry and sexual immorality. Christ names the pattern by its OT type, claiming his knowledge of all Israel's history as the basis for judging the present church.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I gave her time to repent, but she refuses to repent of her sexual immorality.' Christ has already extended patient invitation before issuing the judgment of verses 22-23. The structure reflects Romans 2:4 -- the kindness of God is meant to lead to repentance, and when refused, judgment follows. Christ is not capricious; he has waited. The refusal is hers, not the result of an insufficient offer. This pattern -- patient offer, then judgment -- is the pattern of the whole book: the seals, trumpets, and bowls all follow refused calls to repentance (9:20-21; 16:9,11).</p>""",
    "22": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Behold, I will throw her onto a sickbed, and those who commit adultery with her I will throw into great tribulation, unless they repent of her works.' Christ announces both the judgment and its exit condition in the same sentence. The door of repentance remains open even inside the announcement of coming tribulation -- 'unless they repent' is the consistent grammar of Christ's warnings throughout the seven letters. Judgment and mercy are not opposites in his speech; they are simultaneous offers, one received by repentance and the other by its refusal.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I am he who searches mind and heart, and I will give to each of you according to your works.' This applies Jeremiah 17:10 ('I the LORD search the heart and test the mind, to give every man according to his ways') directly to Christ. The prerogative of omniscient moral judgment -- searching the inner person and rendering verdict according to deeds -- belongs to YHWH in Jeremiah and here belongs to Christ without qualification. All the churches will know that he is the one who searches them: one of the clearest implicit divine-identity claims in the book.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>A direct revelation: 'But to the rest of you in Thyatira, who do not hold this teaching... I do not lay on you any other burden.' Christ distinguishes the faithful remnant from the compromised majority. His pastoral wisdom avoids overloading those who are holding fast: 'the rest' need only to hold fast (v25). The word 'burden' (<em>baros</em>) echoes Acts 15:28 ('no greater burden than these requirements') -- Christ does not heap burdens on the faithful but asks for simple perseverance in what they already have.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Only hold fast what you have until I come.' All perseverance in Revelation is oriented toward the parousia as its horizon and goal. 'Until I come' is not merely a time marker; it is the motivation. The faithful hold fast not because perseverance is intrinsically valuable but because the one they hold fast to is coming -- and their crown (3:11) will be confirmed at his arrival. Every letter in the seven-letter collection anchors endurance in the imminent return of Christ as its sufficient reason.</p>""",
    "26": """<p>A direct revelation: 'The one who conquers and who keeps my works until the end, to him I will give authority over the nations.' Christ applies Psalm 2:8-9 ('I will give you the nations as your heritage; you shall break them with a rod of iron') to the conqueror. The messianic authority that belongs to the Son (Ps 2:7-9) is distributed to those who overcome through union with him -- as Christ received all authority from the Father (Matt 28:18), so he shares that authority with his people. The church's eschatological co-reign is given specifically to those who kept his works.</p>""",
    "27": """<p>A direct revelation: 'he will rule them with a rod of iron, as when earthen pots are broken in pieces, even as I myself have received authority from my Father.' The chain of authority is explicit: Father gives to the Son; Son gives to the conqueror. The authority to rule -- shattering what resists God's reign -- flows downward through the Son to the church. This is the participatory logic of the NT: Christ's victory becomes the church's victory, Christ's inheritance becomes the church's inheritance, because the church is united to him (Rom 8:17; Eph 2:6).</p>""",
    "28": """<p>A direct revelation: 'And I will give him the morning star.' In Revelation 22:16 Christ identifies himself: 'I am the root and descendant of David, the bright morning star.' To give the morning star is to give Christ himself -- or participation in his own glory and identity. The morning star appears at the end of the night, signaling the dawn; Christ is the one whose coming ends the darkness. To receive Christ as the morning star is to receive the dawn of the new creation in which he alone is the light (Rev 21:23).</p>""",
    "29": """<p>A direct revelation: 'He who has an ear, let him hear what the Spirit says to the churches.' This closing formula (repeated in each of the seven letters) establishes that Christ's pastoral word is spoken through and by the Spirit. The Spirit is not a separate voice but the mode through which the risen Christ addresses his people (John 14:26; 16:13-15: 'he will take what is mine and declare it to you'). To hear the Spirit is to hear Christ; the letters are simultaneously Christ's word and the Spirit's word to every church in every age.</p>"""
  },
  "3": {
    "1": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ identifies himself to Sardis as 'him who has the seven spirits of God and the seven stars.' The seven spirits (the sevenfold Spirit of God, Isa 11:2) and the seven stars (the church's messengers) are both under Christ's authority. To a church that 'has a reputation of being alive, but is dead,' Christ presents himself as the one who holds the very Spirit who gives life -- the Spirit can be withheld from a congregation as easily as given. Christ controls the life-giving resource that Sardis lacks.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Wake up, and strengthen what remains and is about to die, for I have not found your works complete in the sight of my God.' The call to 'wake up' (<em>gregoreuon</em>) is resurrection language -- the same call in Ephesians 5:14 ('Awake, O sleeper, and arise from the dead, and Christ will shine on you'). Christ's judgment standard is 'the sight of my God' -- the Father's assessment, which aligns with Christ's own penetrating gaze (2:23). What is incomplete in God's sight is what Christ sees as incomplete; the two assessments are one.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Remember, then, what you received and heard. Keep it, and repent. If you will not wake up, I will come like a thief, and you will not know at what hour I will come against you.' The 'thief in the night' language for Christ's coming appears in Matthew 24:43, 1 Thessalonians 5:2, and 2 Peter 3:10. The unexpected disciplinary coming is a foretaste of the final parousia -- both are Christ's coming, and both catch the sleeping unprepared. The warning to Sardis is a warning to the whole church: spiritual sleep makes Christ's coming a threat rather than a hope.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Yet you have still a few names in Sardis, people who have not soiled their garments, and they will walk with me in white, for they are worthy.' Christ knows the faithful remnant by name. The promise -- 'walk with me in white' -- is intimate: the conquerors will accompany Christ himself in his own purity (19:14: 'clothed in fine linen, white and pure'). Their worthiness is conferred by belonging to Christ; the white garments are his gift (7:14), making their 'worthiness' a participation in his own.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>A direct revelation: three interlocking promises to the conqueror -- white garments (righteousness and victory; 7:14 -- washed white in the blood of the Lamb); name not blotted from the book of life (Exod 32:32-33; Phil 4:3); and 'I will confess his name before my Father and before his angels.' The last promise echoes Matthew 10:32 ('whoever acknowledges me before men, I will also acknowledge before my Father in heaven'). Christ personally confesses each faithful name before the Father -- his advocacy is the ground of the promise.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>A direct revelation: 'He who has an ear, let him hear what the Spirit says to the churches.' The Spirit's voice carries Christ's word to all seven churches simultaneously -- each letter, while addressed to one congregation, is audible to all. The pneumatological formula establishes that the risen Christ's pastoral governance of his church operates through the Spirit's ongoing speech. The instruction to 'hear' implies that the Spirit is still speaking -- these letters are not archived history but living address to the church in every age.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ identifies himself to Philadelphia as 'the holy one, the true one, who has the key of David, who opens and no one will shut, who shuts and no one opens.' 'The holy one' and 'the true one' are divine epithets (Isa 40:25; John 7:18). 'The key of David' applies Isaiah 22:22 -- given to Eliakim the faithful steward who replaces the corrupt Shebna -- directly to Christ. He is the true royal steward with authority over access to the Father's house and kingdom. He opens gospel doors; no imperial power can close them.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Behold, I have set before you an open door, which no one is able to shut.' The open door is the opportunity Christ himself has created -- whether the entrance to the kingdom or the door of gospel witness (2 Cor 2:12; Col 4:3). Philadelphia's 'little strength' is irrelevant: Christ's authority opens the door regardless of the church's size or resources. The promise is not that the church has the power to open doors but that Christ has opened one and no adversary can close it. The church's task is only to walk through what he has already opened.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Behold, I will make those of the synagogue of Satan... bow down before your feet, and they will learn that I have loved you.' Isaiah 60:14 ('the sons of those who afflicted you shall come bending low to you') is applied to the vindication of the Philadelphian church. Christ's love for his people will be publicly confirmed before those who rejected and slandered them. The one who endured rejection will vindicate his beloved -- this is his covenantal pledge to every congregation that has suffered for bearing his name.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Because you have kept my word about patient endurance, I will keep you from the hour of trial that is coming on the whole world.' Faithfulness to Christ's word is answered by Christ's preservation. 'I will keep you' (<em>tereso se</em>) mirrors their 'keeping my word' (<em>eteresaspetronlonmou ton logon</em>) -- the covenant logic of mutual keeping: those who keep Christ's word find that Christ keeps them. Whether the protection is removal from or preservation through the hour of trial, it is Christ's personal commitment to the faithful.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I am coming soon. Hold fast what you have, so that no one may seize your crown.' Christ's imminent return is the horizon and motivation of all endurance throughout the seven letters. 'I am coming soon' (<em>erchomai tachy</em>) is an expression of eschatological certainty -- his return is the next thing, and nothing stands between the church and it but his own purpose. The crown belongs to those who hold fast; they are in danger only of letting it be seized by spiritual compromise before he arrives.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>A direct revelation: four promises converge on the conqueror: pillar in the temple (permanent, irremovable presence in God's household; cf. 21:22 where the whole city is the temple); 'the name of my God' written on them (belonging to the Father, identified as his); 'the name of the city of my God, the new Jerusalem' (citizenship in the eschatological city, 21:2); 'my own new name' -- the risen Christ's glorious, not-yet-revealed name (19:12) inscribed on the faithful. The conqueror is named with every name that matters: God, city, and Christ himself.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>A direct revelation: 'He who has an ear, let him hear what the Spirit says to the churches.' The sixth iteration of this formula seals the Philadelphian letter as part of the single divine word that Christ speaks through the Spirit to all seven churches. The repetition of the formula across all seven letters establishes a unified address: all seven churches hear what is said to each -- the whole church in every age is the audience of the complete collection, which is the risen Christ's pastoral address to his body through the Spirit.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>A direct revelation: Christ identifies himself to Laodicea as 'the Amen, the faithful and true witness, the beginning of God's creation.' 'The Amen' -- in 2 Corinthians 1:20 all God's promises find their 'yes' in Christ; he is the affirmation of every covenant promise. 'The faithful and true witness' (cf. 1:5; 19:11) is his self-description as the one whose word can be trusted absolutely. 'The beginning of God's creation' (<em>arche tes ktiseos</em>) -- Colossians 1:15,18 -- not the first creature but the source and head of all creation. To the self-sufficient Laodiceans, Christ presents himself as the one on whom everything depends.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I know your works: you are neither cold nor hot. Would that you were either cold or hot!' The lukewarm church is the most troubling condition in Christ's pastoral assessment -- not active opposition (cold) or fervent devotion (hot) but the comfortable indifference of the self-sufficient. Christ would prefer either extreme to the middle: cold rejection at least knows what it is doing; fervent love is what he desires. Indifference is the condition most resistant to the gospel because it feels no need for anything Christ offers.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>A direct revelation: 'So, because you are lukewarm, and neither hot nor cold, I will spit you out of my mouth.' The Laodicean church will be expelled from intimate fellowship with Christ. The 'spitting out' (<em>emesai</em>) is visceral: what is lukewarm nauseates rather than satisfies. Christ is not indifferent to indifference; he responds to it with the strongest expression of rejection in the seven letters. The church that is comfortable with Christ but not fervent for him faces being expelled from his presence -- the most severe pastoral warning in Revelation.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>A direct revelation: 'For you say, I am rich, I have prospered, and I need nothing, not realizing that you are wretched, pitiable, poor, blind, and naked.' The five-fold inventory of Laodicea's true condition -- from Christ's perspective -- stands against their own three-fold self-assessment. Laodicea was famous for its banking, textile industry, and medical school (eye salve); Christ inverts each: they are poor, naked, and blind. Only his assessment is accurate; their comfort has corrupted their self-knowledge. This is the danger of prosperity: it generates a self-sufficiency that closes the eyes to spiritual destitution.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>A direct revelation: 'I counsel you to buy from me gold refined by fire, so that you may be rich, and white garments so that you may clothe yourself, and salve to anoint your eyes, so that you may see.' Christ offers the genuine versions of everything Laodicea falsely claimed to have: true gold (faith tested by suffering, 1 Pet 1:7), true white garments (the righteousness he gives, not Laodicea's wool), true sight (spiritual perception his anointing provides). All three must be bought 'from me' -- they cannot be manufactured by wealth or self-effort. Christ alone supplies what the self-sufficient church lacks.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Those whom I love, I reprove and discipline, so be zealous and repent.' Christ cites Proverbs 3:12 ('the LORD reproves him whom he loves, as a father the son in whom he delights'), which Hebrews 12:6 applies to the experience of God's children. The discipline of the Laodicean letter -- the shattering verdict of verses 15-18 -- is itself an act of love. Christ does not abandon the comfortable and compromised; he confronts them. The very severity of the rebuke is proof that he has not written them off.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Behold, I stand at the door and knock. If anyone hears my voice and opens the door, I will come in to him and eat with him, and he with me.' The imagery of table fellowship -- eating together -- is consistently the sign of intimate restored relationship in the Gospels (Luke 15:23; 19:5-7; John 21:12-13; Acts 10:41). Christ seeks entry into the lukewarm church not with judgment but with the offer of intimacy. That the sovereign Lord of the universe stands at the door and knocks, waiting for the church to open from the inside, is the posture of patient grace in the face of indifference.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>A direct revelation: 'The one who conquers, I will grant him to sit with me on my throne, as I also conquered and sat down with my Father on his throne.' The participatory chain of victory: Father enthroned → Son conquers → sits with Father; conqueror conquers → sits with Son. Christ's own exaltation (Phil 2:9-11; Heb 12:2: 'sat down at the right hand of the throne of God') is the template for the conqueror's exaltation. The church's eschatological co-reign (Rev 20:4-6; 2 Tim 2:12) is grounded in union with Christ who first conquered and sat down.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>A direct revelation: 'He who has an ear, let him hear what the Spirit says to the churches.' The final iteration of the formula closes the seven-letter corpus. Christ's address through the Spirit to the seven churches is complete -- seven letters, seven conditions, seven sets of commendations and rebukes, seven promises to the conqueror. The whole collection forms the risen Christ's pastoral word to the whole church, speaking through the Spirit who takes what is Christ's and declares it (John 16:14-15) to every church in every age that has ears to hear.</p>"""
  },
  "4": {
    "1": """<p>A thematic connection: 'After this I looked, and behold, a door standing open in heaven!' The open door recalls Christ's own promise in 3:8 ('I have set before you an open door') and his self-identification as the one who opens what no one shuts. The voice 'like a trumpet' that calls John up is the same Christ-voice of 1:10-11. John ascends in the Spirit to see 'what must take place after this' -- a phrase drawn from Daniel 2:28-29 (the revelation given to Daniel about end-time events). The throne room vision is Christ's invitation to see what he alone can show.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>A thematic connection: the throne in heaven and 'one seated on the throne' -- the Father's transcendent majesty. The vision of the divine throne (Isa 6:1-3; Ezek 1:26-28; Dan 7:9) is the necessary context for understanding what follows in chapter 5. The Father's sovereign throne is the seat from which the Lamb will receive the scroll. Everything in Revelation -- every judgment, every salvation -- flows from the authority of the one seated here. This is also the throne on which the Lamb and the Father will sit together (3:21; 5:6-7; 22:1,3).</p>""",
    "3": """<p>A thematic connection: the appearance of jasper and carnelian glory, with a rainbow of emerald around the throne. Ezekiel 1:28 describes 'the appearance of the likeness of the glory of the LORD' in rainbow-and-fire language, and Revelation 21:11 describes the New Jerusalem with jasper brilliance. The divine glory revealed in the throne room is the same glory the Lamb shares (5:12-13) and that fills the new creation (21:23: 'the glory of God gives it light, and its lamp is the Lamb'). The throne room is the source of the glory that ultimately transforms all things.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>A thematic connection: twenty-four elders clothed in white with golden crowns surround the throne. The elders likely represent the full people of God -- twelve patriarchs of Israel and twelve apostles of the Lamb (cf. 21:12-14) -- the whole covenant community, OT and NT, gathered in the throne room. Their white garments are the gift of Christ (3:5; 7:14: 'washed white in the blood of the Lamb'). Their crowns are the victor's crowns they will cast before the throne (4:10) and before the Lamb (5:8-14). They are there because of what Christ accomplished.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>A thematic connection: 'From the throne came flashes of lightning, and rumblings and peals of thunder, and before the throne were burning seven torches of fire, which are the seven spirits of God.' The Sinai theophany (Exod 19:16-19 -- lightning, thunder, the divine presence) is transported to the heavenly throne room. The seven torches of fire are identified as 'the seven spirits of God' -- the same sevenfold Spirit that Christ holds (3:1) and that the Lamb has as his seven eyes (5:6). The Spirit who fills the throne room is the Spirit of Christ, sent from the throne through the Lamb.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>A thematic connection: 'Before the throne there was as it were a sea of glass, like crystal.' The sea in Hebrew cosmology represents chaos, death, and the forces opposing God's order. That the sea before the throne is glass -- still, transparent, conquered -- declares that God reigns over all chaos absolutely. The redeemed in 15:2 will 'stand beside the sea of glass' after their victory. In 21:1 'the sea was no more' -- it is completely overcome by Christ's triumph. The glassy sea frames the setting of the Lamb's worthiness that chapter 5 will display.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>A thematic connection: the four living creatures -- like a lion, an ox, a man, and an eagle -- represent the fullness of created life worshiping before God (Ezek 1:5-14; Isa 6:2). Irenaeus connected these four faces to the four Gospel portraits of Christ (lion/Matthew-kingly, ox/Luke-priestly, man/John-incarnate, eagle/Mark-prophetic), reflecting the patristic instinct that the living creatures mediate between the Creator's throne-room glory and the new creation's redemption through Christ. The creatures lead the worship into which the Lamb is inserted in chapter 5.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>A thematic connection: the four living creatures sing without ceasing, 'Holy, holy, holy, is the Lord God Almighty, who was and is and is to come!' The Trisagion of Isaiah 6:3 -- the worship that filled the temple in Isaiah's commissioning vision -- is now the unceasing worship of the heavenly throne room. John 12:41 states that Isaiah 'saw his glory and spoke of him' -- the 'him' being Christ. The seraphic worship of the holy God in Isaiah's vision was directed at the pre-incarnate Son. The throne-room Trisagion is thus continuous with the worship of Christ that chapter 5 makes explicit.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>A thematic connection: 'whenever the living creatures give glory and honor and thanks to him who is seated on the throne, who lives forever and ever...' The worship of the one on the throne is the frame into which the Lamb's worship is inserted in 5:8-14. The same language -- 'glory and honor' -- appears in 5:12 as the sevenfold acclamation of the Lamb. The deliberate verbal parallelism shows that the Lamb receives the same quality and kind of worship as the Father, establishing his full divine status within the throne room's worship economy.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>A thematic connection: 'the twenty-four elders fall down before him who is seated on the throne and worship him who lives forever and ever. They cast their crowns before the throne.' The elders' prostration before the Father in 4:10 is mirrored by their prostration before the Lamb in 5:8. The same redeemed community that worships the Father's sovereignty worships the Lamb's redemptive worthiness with the same act. The casting of crowns is the acknowledgment that every victory they have is received from God -- and in chapter 5, they recognize that it was received through the Lamb's sacrifice.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>A thematic connection: 'Worthy are you, our Lord and God, to receive glory and honor and power, for you created all things, and by your will they existed and were created.' The first 'worthy' (<em>axios</em>) acclamation in Revelation is directed to the Creator. In 5:9 the exact word recurs: 'Worthy are you to take the scroll and to open its seals' -- directed to the Lamb. Creation-worthiness and redemption-worthiness are attributed by the same word to God and to Christ. The Creator who made all things by his will is the same Christ through whom all things were made (John 1:3; Col 1:16).</p>"""
  },
  "5": {
    "1": """<p>A direct revelation: in the right hand of the one on the throne is a scroll sealed with seven seals -- the title deed of creation and the plan of history's consummation. The scroll can only be opened by one who has the authority and qualifications. That no creature can open it (v3) and that only the Lamb can (v9) establishes the Christological claim: access to the meaning and direction of all history is held by Christ alone. The sealed scroll frames the entire cosmic drama that follows: who governs history, and by what right?</p>""",
    "2": """<p>A direct revelation: 'A mighty angel proclaiming with a loud voice, Who is worthy to open the scroll and break its seals?' The cosmic question posed by the angel frames the central Christological inquiry of Revelation and of all history: who is qualified to direct history toward its appointed end? Worthiness requires both the authority of the sovereign and the qualifications of the redeemer. The question is posed publicly so that the answer -- only the Lamb -- is heard by every creature in heaven and earth and under the earth (v13).</p>""",
    "3": """<p>A type fulfilled: 'No one in heaven or on earth or under the earth was able to open the scroll or to look into it.' The impossibility of any creature achieving what Christ alone achieves is the structural argument of Hebrews 9-10: no human priest's sacrifice, no angel's intercession, no created being's merit can accomplish the redemption and governance the scroll's opening represents. The comprehensive scope -- heaven, earth, under the earth -- establishes the total failure of all creaturely resources before the need that only the incarnate, crucified, and risen Son can meet.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>A direct revelation: 'and I began to weep loudly because no one was found worthy to open the scroll or to look into it.' John's weeping is the representative grief of all creation for a locked history -- unredeemed, without a future, under the dominion of death and sin. The weeping that ceases in verse 5 when the Lion-Lamb is announced is the tears that cease at the cross and resurrection. Paul's language in Romans 8:19-22 -- creation groaning in futility -- is the cosmic correlate of John's weeping before the sealed scroll.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Behold, the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David, has conquered, so that he can open the scroll and its seven seals.' Two foundational messianic titles: Lion of Judah (Gen 49:9-10: 'the scepter shall not depart from Judah') and Root of David (Isa 11:1,10: 'a shoot from the stump of Jesse'). His conquest (<em>enikesen</em>, aorist) is the cross and resurrection -- the counter-intuitive victory of dying to defeat death. John then turns to see the Lion and sees instead a Lamb standing as though slain (v6): the cross is how the Lion conquered.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>A direct revelation: 'And he went and took the scroll from the right hand of him who was seated on the throne.' The Lamb's act of taking the scroll is the structural pivot of the entire book. This action transfers authority over creation's consummation to the one who qualified by his blood. John 17:2 ('you have given him authority over all flesh') and Daniel 7:14 ('to him was given dominion and glory and a kingdom') converge in this single act. Everything in Revelation 6-22 unfolds from the Lamb taking the scroll.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>A direct revelation: 'the four living creatures and the twenty-four elders fell down before the Lamb, each holding a harp, and golden bowls full of incense, which are the prayers of the saints.' The transfer of worship from God alone in chapter 4 to the Lamb in chapter 5 is the most theologically dense moment of Revelation. The golden bowls of incense -- the prayers of the saints (Ps 141:2) -- rise before the Lamb, who is their mediator and intercessor (1 Tim 2:5; Heb 7:25: 'he always lives to make intercession for them'). The prayers Christians offer are held by the crucified-risen Lord.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Worthy are you to take the scroll and to open its seals, for you were slain and by your blood you ransomed people for God from every tribe and language and people and nation.' The new song (Ps 33:3; 40:3; 96:1 -- new songs celebrate new acts of God) identifies the precise ground of the Lamb's worthiness: the substitutionary atonement. 'You were slain' and 'by your blood you ransomed' are the two clauses that qualify him for cosmic sovereignty. Universal in scope -- every tribe, language, people, nation -- this is the centripetal statement of Revelation's Christology.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>A direct revelation: 'and you have made them a kingdom and priests to our God, and they shall reign on the earth.' The new song continues: Exodus 19:6 ('a kingdom of priests and a holy nation') is fulfilled by the blood of the Lamb from every nation. The vocation Israel failed to maintain under the old covenant is now constituted by Christ's redemption from every people. The reign 'on the earth' is both present (the church's priestly mediation) and eschatological (20:4-6 -- co-reign with Christ). The Lamb's blood is the constitutional foundation of the priestly-royal church.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>A direct revelation: 'Then I looked and heard the voice of many angels around the throne... numbering myriads of myriads and thousands of thousands.' The worship of the Lamb expands from the elders and living creatures to the full angelic host. Hebrews 1:6 ('when he brings the firstborn into the world, he says, Let all God's angels worship him') is enacted here: the angelic proclamation of Christ's worthiness is the heavenly fulfillment of the Father's command. The number -- innumerable -- suggests the totality of the heavenly court directing its worship toward the crucified-risen Lamb.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>A direct revelation: 'And I heard every creature in heaven and on earth and under the earth and in the sea, saying, To him who sits on the throne and to the Lamb be blessing and honor and glory and might forever and ever!' The doxology addressed equally to the Father and the Lamb establishes the Lamb's full divine status: what belongs to the Creator belongs also to the Redeemer. Philippians 2:10-11 ('every knee shall bow... every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord') is cosmically enacted here. The Lamb stands at the center of all creation's worship, jointly with the Father, forever.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>A direct revelation: 'And the four living creatures said, Amen! and the elders fell down and worshiped.' The 'Amen' that closes the throne-room vision is the word Christ uses of himself in 3:14: 'the Amen, the faithful and true witness.' The living creatures' Amen to the cosmic doxology of verse 13 is, appropriately, the word that names Christ himself -- the affirmation that all God's promises find in him (2 Cor 1:20). The elders' prostration before the Lamb mirrors their prostration before the Father in 4:10, sealing the equality of their worship and the Lamb's full participation in the divine identity.</p>"""
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm("mkt-christ", "revelation")
    before_count = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    merge_comm(existing, REVELATION_CHRIST)
    save_comm("mkt-christ", "revelation", existing)

    result = load_comm("mkt-christ", "revelation")
    after_count = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f"  Verses added: {after_count - before_count}")
    for ch in range(1, 6):
        ck = str(ch)
        n = len(result.get(ck, {}))
        print(f"  Ch {ch}: {n} verses present")
    total_chs = len(result)
    total_vv = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f"  Revelation total: {total_chs} chapters, {total_vv} verses with christ data")
    print("Revelation 1-5 christ fill written.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
